<TITLE> Sufia Kamal remembered </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 20 (bdnews24.com)  Cultural and social organisations on Friday remembered pre-eminent poet Sufia Kamal with a variety of programmes on her 10th death anniversary. Bangabandhu Sangskritik Jote and Sufia Kamal Smrity Sangsad paid tribute to her by placing flowers at her graveyard in the morning. In addition, various organisations hosted discussions on her life and work. Kamal, born in Barisal in 1911, died at Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujib Medical University on Nov 20, 1999. She was also a women-rights campaign leader and a pioneer of many movements, including against religious bigotry and communality. She spent her life on women empowerment and literary works. Kamal took an active part in every freedom struggle of the Bengali nation, including language movement, freedom movement, liberation war and anti-autocracy movement. Her first book of poems, Sanjher Maya, came out in 1938. Among her other notable works are Maya Kajol, Mon and Jibon, Udatto Prithibi and Obhijatrik. She also wrote quite a number of short stories, including 'Keyar Kanta'. Kamal was awarded with a host of prizes from home and abroad, including Bangla Academy Award, Ekushey Padak, Begum Rokeya Padak, and Independence Day Award. MP Tarana Halim, actors ATM Shamsuzzaman and Dilara Yasmin, movie stars Mizu Ahmed and Faruk, poet Halim Azad, among others, were present at the discussion at Gulshan office of Bangabandhu Sanskritik Jote. Prime minister Sheikh Hasina gave a message. "After the brutal killing of Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman on Aug 15, 1975, her rebel voice motivated the forces of liberation war to reorganise with a new inspiration." She paid her deepest respect to Sufia Kamal's memories for being a pioneer in free thinking and spirit. bdne
